\label{def:TailMove}
Let $e=(u,v)$ and $f$ be edges of a  network. A tail move of $e$ to $f$ consists of the following steps:
\begin{enumerate}
\item deleting $e$;
\item subdividing $f$ with a new node $u'$;
\item suppressing the indegree-1 outdegree-1 node $u$;
\item adding the edge $(u',v)$.
\end{enumerate}
Tail moves are only allowed if the resulting digraph is still a network, see Definition \ref{def:networkTree}.
We say that a tail move is a \emph{distance-$d$} move if, after step 2, a shortest path from $u$ to $u'$ in the underlying undirected graph has length $d+1$.

