\label{Thm:Main}
Let $n,k,$ and $q$ be integers such that $1 \leq k \leq \lfloor n/2 \rfloor -1$
and $1 \leq q \leq n-1$.
Denote by $f(n,k,q)$ the maximal number of edges in an $I_{k+1}$-free CGG on $n$
vertices that admits a free boundary arc of order $q$. Then:
\begin{enumerate}
\item If $q \leq n-2k$, then $f(n,k,q)=kn$. In particular, there exists a \emph{maximal}
$I_{k+1}$-free CGG that admits a free boundary arc of order $q$.

