Let $v\in V(G)$. A divisor $D$ is said to be $v$-\emph{reduced} if:
\begin{enumerate}
\item  the divisor $D$ is ``effective away from $v$'' -- that is, for all $w\in V(G) \smallsetminus \{ v \}$, $D(w)\geq 0$, and
\item  for any $U\subset V(G)\smallsetminus \{ v \}$, the divisor obtained by firing all vertices in $U$ is not effective away from $v$.
